04:14.852 --> 04:16.151
MARISSA: $10,000

04:16.153 --> 04:18.070
for Hamilton tickets, day of,

04:18.072 --> 04:20.189
fourth row center, from a scalper.

04:20.190 --> 04:22.942
It's an absolutely justifiable
business expense.

04:22.944 --> 04:24.693
I had to pay off the court clerk.

04:24.695 --> 04:27.746
Bull, I seriously doubt
the IRS will agree

04:27.748 --> 04:29.581
that illegal bribes are deductible.

04:29.583 --> 04:33.035
Marissa, if I don't have a list
of the 75 potential jurors

04:33.037 --> 04:35.004
that make up the jury pool
at least a couple days

04:35.006 --> 04:36.372
before I walk into that courtroom,

04:36.374 --> 04:38.624
then all of those people
on the other side of that door

04:38.626 --> 04:40.542
can't research them
and help me figure out

04:40.544 --> 04:41.844
if I want them or not.

04:41.846 --> 04:43.846
And since jury lists
are not supposed to be shared

04:43.848 --> 04:45.130
- with either side,
- Exactly.

04:45.132 --> 04:46.181
The only way that I can do

04:46.183 --> 04:47.716
my job is to have that list.

04:47.718 --> 04:49.435
Otherwise, I'm just guessing.

04:49.437 --> 04:51.553
- And any fool can guess.
- (KNOCKING)

04:51.555 --> 04:53.389
- Come in!
- ‭Bad time?

04:53.391 --> 04:55.975
No. No, no. Perfect time.

04:55.977 --> 04:57.860
How was the memorial service?

04:58.480 --> 05:00.112
CABLE: Uh, I-I don't know.

05:00.114 --> 05:02.231
I don't have anything to compare it to.

05:02.233 --> 05:04.704
I've never had a friend die before.

05:05.389 --> 05:08.156
Is there any way
I could talk to you alone?

05:08.181 --> 05:09.738
CABLE: I know you didn't
know Simon very well.

05:09.740 --> 05:11.707
(SIGHS) Cable,

05:11.709 --> 05:14.076
a lot of assistants come through here.

05:16.383 --> 05:18.163
- It's no excuse.
- You know, the only reason

05:18.165 --> 05:20.632
he left here is because
he couldn't do nine-to-five.

05:20.634 --> 05:24.086
Everything had to be
his choice, all the time.

05:24.088 --> 05:25.754
When to wake up, what to do.

05:25.756 --> 05:27.923
Anyway, I'm sure somebody told you,

05:27.925 --> 05:29.758
but he started working
as a bike messenger.

05:29.760 --> 05:31.260
It was kind of invented for him,

05:31.262 --> 05:33.762
because he could just text
when he felt like working.

05:33.764 --> 05:36.765
And the other thing
he started to do, actually,

05:36.767 --> 05:39.101
about a year ago,
while he was working here,

05:39.103 --> 05:42.771
was working as a guinea pig
for pharmaceutical companies,

05:42.773 --> 05:44.490
testing new drugs.

05:44.492 --> 05:45.774
They pay a lot of money.

05:45.776 --> 05:47.359
And all he had to do was remember

05:47.361 --> 05:48.827
to take one or two pills a day.

05:49.432 --> 05:50.612
I know you really cared for him...

05:50.614 --> 05:52.587
I was talking to some of his friends.

05:52.961 --> 05:55.000
It turns out he was doing
a trial for this company

05:55.002 --> 05:56.535
called Dep Pharmaceutical,

05:56.537 --> 05:59.038
testing this new kind of
antidepressant called Eutaline.

06:00.218 --> 06:02.762
The people that know Simon,

06:03.680 --> 06:06.462
they say it was the drug that
caused Simon to kill himself.

06:06.464 --> 06:09.298
- Cable, when people are grieving...
- ‭They say

06:09.300 --> 06:10.966
- he completely changed on it.
- Even so,

06:10.968 --> 06:12.801
- it doesn't mean it made him suicidal.
- That man

06:12.803 --> 06:16.438
loved life. He didn't drink, he
didn't smoke, he loved the gym.

06:16.440 --> 06:18.236
But he took pills for money.

06:19.488 --> 06:21.610
Look, his parents want to sue.

06:22.949 --> 06:25.114
And I told them I'd help.

06:26.786 --> 06:29.902
And I told them
I'd ask you if you'd help.

06:31.666 --> 06:33.072
They want money?

06:33.074 --> 06:34.656
They want answers.

06:34.658 --> 06:38.077
And they want to make sure
this drug never gets to market.

06:38.996 --> 06:41.296
And, yes, I'm sure they want money, too.

06:41.298 --> 06:42.761
Hmm.

06:44.387 --> 06:46.085
Let me call Dep Pharmaceutical,

06:46.087 --> 06:49.088
see if I can't put a meeting
on the books for Benny and me.

06:49.090 --> 06:51.140
BENNY: Nice of you to do this.

06:51.142 --> 06:53.008
Represent someone I don't remember

06:53.010 --> 06:54.927
on a matter I know almost nothing about

06:54.929 --> 06:57.763
to make his parents, whom
I've never met, feel better?

06:58.151 --> 07:00.015
- Yeah, I'm a peach.
- ‭(CHUCKLES)

07:02.186 --> 07:05.320
- (HEELS CLICKING)
- I sense our meeting is about to begin.

07:05.322 --> 07:06.688
(DOOR OPENS)

07:08.366 --> 07:11.276
Dr. Bull, you have no idea

07:11.278 --> 07:13.612
what a treat it is for me to meet you.

07:13.614 --> 07:16.248
And Benjamin Colón, former ADA.

07:16.250 --> 07:19.835
For New York County and
in-house counsel for TAC.

07:19.837 --> 07:21.703
My name is Arti Cander.

07:21.705 --> 07:23.455
Please, have a seat.

07:25.991 --> 07:27.759
So you know why we're here?

07:28.056 --> 07:29.344
Absolutely.

07:29.346 --> 07:31.713
Our cofounder and CEO, Tessa Snyder,

07:31.715 --> 07:33.715
is beside herself about this.

07:33.717 --> 07:36.051
You know, any time anyone who is part

07:36.053 --> 07:37.386
of the Dep family passes,

07:37.388 --> 07:39.972
no matter how minor their role
in the company might be,

07:39.974 --> 07:41.557
it-it saddens all of us.

07:41.559 --> 07:43.725
You do understand we believe
there's a relationship

07:43.727 --> 07:45.194
between Mr. Jones' death

07:45.196 --> 07:48.197
and the antidepressant
he was testing for Dep.

07:48.199 --> 07:50.449
Really? I was, uh, under the impression

07:50.451 --> 07:52.734
- that he fell off a roof.
- BENNY: Mm.

07:53.039 --> 07:54.570
Jumped.

07:56.001 --> 07:57.573
Well, this is the first I've heard

07:57.575 --> 08:01.210
of any suicidal ideation
in relationship to this drug.

08:01.395 --> 08:03.428
Um, have you gentlemen...

08:03.430 --> 08:05.597
have you gentlemen done your homework?

08:05.599 --> 08:08.400
You know, if this side effect
was even on our radar,

08:08.402 --> 08:09.984
we wouldn't be doing human trials.

08:09.986 --> 08:12.270
Um, FDA would simply not hear of it.

08:12.559 --> 08:15.523
Now, what can I do for you?

08:15.525 --> 08:17.359
You can shoot off a flare

08:17.361 --> 08:19.611
and let everybody at the...

08:19.613 --> 08:21.112
Dep family

08:21.114 --> 08:23.782
know that we're not gonna
take you at your word

08:23.784 --> 08:25.617
that the new happy pill
you're getting ready to inflict

08:25.619 --> 08:28.086
on the general public doesn't, in fact,

08:28.088 --> 08:31.840
make people want to shut off
the lights and call it a day.

08:31.842 --> 08:33.625
If you're looking for a settlement...

08:33.626 --> 08:35.376
Oh, no. Thank you, Ms. Cander.

08:35.379 --> 08:36.760
Quite the name, by the way.

08:36.763 --> 08:39.047
Nothing like a little irony
on your driver's license

08:39.049 --> 08:40.965
to keep your mood in check.

08:40.967 --> 08:42.851
Says the man named Bull.

08:42.852 --> 08:44.386
- Mm.
- ‭Let me save you some time,

08:44.388 --> 08:47.639
Arti, Simon's family is not gonna settle,

08:47.641 --> 08:48.890
and there's no amount of money

08:48.892 --> 08:50.859
that's gonna convince them otherwise.

08:51.556 --> 08:52.777
Oh, my.

08:52.779 --> 08:55.363
The famous Dr. Jason Bull,

08:55.365 --> 08:58.616
expert reader of human behavior,
just misread me.

08:58.618 --> 09:00.735
We have no interest in settling.

09:00.737 --> 09:01.900
None.

09:02.213 --> 09:03.905
We're very happy to prove
in a court of law

09:03.907 --> 09:06.324
that this drug is perfectly safe.

09:06.326 --> 09:07.325
It may not be safe.

09:07.327 --> 09:09.077
- A man died while taking it.
- ‭Ah.

09:09.079 --> 09:10.408
So you say.

09:10.997 --> 09:12.831
Then court it shall be.

09:12.833 --> 09:14.663
Excellent.

09:15.302 --> 09:17.919
I assume you're general counsel
for Dep Pharmaceutical.

09:17.921 --> 09:19.671
Can I trouble you for a card?

09:19.673 --> 09:22.006
I'm sorry to disappoint you, Dr. Bull,

09:22.008 --> 09:24.426
but I'm not general counsel for Dep.

09:24.428 --> 09:26.010
Then to whom have I been speaking?

09:26.012 --> 09:27.896
I work for Tessa Snyder.

09:28.218 --> 09:30.014
I'm her you.

09:30.016 --> 09:32.016
(CHUCKLES) Excuse me?

09:32.018 --> 09:33.568
I'm a trial scientist, Dr. Bull.

09:33.570 --> 09:35.937
And I very much look forward
to seeing you in court.

09:36.735 --> 09:39.190
Please, feel free to let yourselves out.

09:44.331 --> 09:52.410
Synced & corrected by -robtor-
www.addic7ed.com

09:53.209 --> 09:55.459
♪ ♪

09:57.547 --> 09:59.914
(BULL SIGHS)

10:04.228 --> 10:06.395
- (DOOR OPENS)
- BENNY: Hey.

10:06.397 --> 10:08.216
You gonna be joining us?

10:08.766 --> 10:10.699
No. Go ahead without me.

10:11.094 --> 10:12.466
BENNY: The big news is

10:12.847 --> 10:16.355
Dep Pharmaceutical is downright
anxious to go to court.

10:16.357 --> 10:19.157
Which leads me to believe
that they have rock solid

10:19.159 --> 10:21.109
information on Simon

10:21.111 --> 10:24.079
that they believe clears
them of any culpability.

10:24.691 --> 10:25.781
Cable?

10:25.783 --> 10:27.532
I'm digging, but, honestly,

10:27.534 --> 10:29.785
I don't think there's any "there" there.

10:29.787 --> 10:31.920
I knew Simon. We all did.

10:32.741 --> 10:34.256
Wh-What about the company itself?

10:34.909 --> 10:36.758
This is Tessa Snyder,

10:36.760 --> 10:38.010
the company CEO.

10:38.012 --> 10:40.679
A competitor once described her
as "a burning hot pepper

10:40.681 --> 10:42.464
disguised as an ice cream sundae ""

10:42.466 --> 10:44.961
Wow. Can't wait to meet her.

10:46.004 --> 10:47.803
Danny? ‭Well, I'm trying to get a list

10:47.805 --> 10:49.388
of the other participants in the study.

10:49.390 --> 10:51.607
And, believe it or not,
I may have a lead.

10:51.609 --> 10:52.975
Okay. (CLICKS TONGUE)

10:52.977 --> 10:56.144
Well, I guess we'll wait
to hear from the big guy

10:56.146 --> 10:57.396
about voir dire.

10:57.398 --> 10:58.924
What's he doing in there?

10:58.926 --> 11:00.148
It's not what.

11:00.150 --> 11:01.853
It's who.

11:04.520 --> 11:06.604
BULL: Wait a second! Isn't that London's

11:06.606 --> 11:07.585
Arti Cander?

11:07.587 --> 11:09.240
Is there nothing she can't do?

11:09.242 --> 11:11.525
Graduated with honors from
Oxford, then moved to D.C.

11:11.527 --> 11:13.694
to became a lobbyist
in the candy industry.

11:13.696 --> 11:15.661
Tough job. No one likes candy.

11:15.688 --> 11:17.688
And then decided to start all over again

11:17.690 --> 11:19.190
and enter the trial science business.

11:19.192 --> 11:22.193
Mm. Someone figured out how to Google.

11:22.195 --> 11:23.778
You left out the part

11:23.780 --> 11:25.413
where I spent three years at Georgetown

11:25.415 --> 11:26.998
studying law and human behavior.

11:27.000 --> 11:28.115
Oh, and you.

11:28.117 --> 11:30.534
I forgot to mention this
the other day, but

11:30.536 --> 11:32.370
I firmly do believe that you are one

11:32.372 --> 11:33.968
of the two best at what you do.

11:33.970 --> 11:35.456
Wait. Is this the part where

11:35.458 --> 11:36.920
I'm supposed to say,
"But who's the other""

11:36.922 --> 11:39.844
Oh, you don't have to say it...
just as long as you think it.

11:40.233 --> 11:42.233
So is it true you don't
use mirror jurors?

11:42.235 --> 11:43.685
Yeah, I've never really seen the point.

11:43.687 --> 11:45.531
It's an extrapolation once removed.

11:45.533 --> 11:47.188
Then how do you know what
the jurors are thinking?

11:47.190 --> 11:49.607
I read them... all by myself.

11:49.609 --> 11:51.025
You should try it sometime.

11:51.027 --> 11:52.861
Oh, I wouldn't know where to begin.

11:52.863 --> 11:55.997
Perhaps after I've had
the opportunity to study you.

11:56.407 --> 11:59.534
Sorry. We're not taking
any new students at the moment.

11:59.536 --> 12:01.336
I'll see you in court, Dr. Bull.

12:03.840 --> 12:05.874
(LOW CONVERSATIONS)

12:06.626 --> 12:07.959
BENNY: There he is.

12:07.961 --> 12:11.629
Dr. Jason Bull, this is Mr.
and Mrs. Jones, Simon's parents.

12:11.631 --> 12:13.798
Thank you for doing this, Dr. Bull.

12:13.800 --> 12:16.384
Well, we haven't done anything
yet, but you're very welcome.

12:16.386 --> 12:18.513
Do you mind if I steal
Mr. Colón for a moment?

12:19.055 --> 12:20.348
Excuse me.

12:25.019 --> 12:28.396
I am totally in the dark about
our approach to voir dire.

12:28.398 --> 12:30.064
MARISSA (OVER EARBUD):
That would make two of us, Bull.

12:30.066 --> 12:31.533
Is it as simple as finding people

12:31.535 --> 12:34.035
who feel anger towards
the pharmaceutical companies?

12:34.037 --> 12:35.570
'Cause there are plenty of those.

12:35.572 --> 12:37.038
I wish. No.

12:37.625 --> 12:38.990
Just because people are mad at a company

12:38.992 --> 12:40.792
or even an entire industry doesn't mean

12:40.794 --> 12:42.076
they're gonna side with us.

12:42.453 --> 12:45.413
Shared experience does not equal empathy.

12:46.040 --> 12:48.132
In fact, a lot of times,
it's just the opposite.

12:48.134 --> 12:50.218
It's called the empathy gap.

12:50.220 --> 12:53.471
I worry that they are gonna
see Simon as someone

12:53.473 --> 12:56.724
who willingly signed up
for a risky job in an industry

12:56.726 --> 12:58.676
famous for its greed and arrogance,

12:58.678 --> 13:00.511
and should have known better.

13:00.513 --> 13:02.564
Mm-hmm. So, what are we looking for?

13:02.566 --> 13:04.482
Perversely, I am thinking

13:04.484 --> 13:08.486
of going after jurors who
trust powerful corporations.

13:08.488 --> 13:09.938
Now I'm confused.

13:09.940 --> 13:11.439
I would've thought that's
exactly who we don't want.

13:11.441 --> 13:12.607
BULL: Think about it.

13:12.609 --> 13:15.159
Who better to understand
what happened to Simon

13:15.161 --> 13:18.446
than someone who takes
big companies at their word.

13:18.448 --> 13:20.832
We'll tell them a story about a young man

13:20.834 --> 13:23.201
who trusted the people he worked for,

13:23.203 --> 13:25.954
never questioning their intentions

13:25.956 --> 13:28.623
or their honesty till it was too late.

13:29.375 --> 13:32.627
And hopefully, we'll shock 'em
into siding with us.

13:33.129 --> 13:35.179
Mm. Well,

13:35.840 --> 13:38.216
at the very least,
she'll never see it coming.

13:38.635 --> 13:40.268
MARISSA: Eddie Dunn, 33 years old.

13:40.270 --> 13:42.136
He is a toy wholesaler, so,

13:42.138 --> 13:45.139
he depends on big manufacturers
for his livelihood.

13:45.141 --> 13:47.475
He is the poster boy
for the kind of juror they think

13:47.477 --> 13:49.444
they want and think we don't.

13:49.446 --> 13:50.979
Excellent. This should be fun.

13:50.981 --> 13:52.363
ATTORNEY: Say you buy a product...

13:52.365 --> 13:54.616
sandwich bags... you get them home,

13:54.618 --> 13:56.784
but none of the zippers work.

13:56.786 --> 13:58.736
What do you do? Do you drive

13:58.738 --> 14:00.488
all the way back to the store

14:00.490 --> 14:02.790
and make them exchange
it for another box?

14:02.792 --> 14:04.993
Do you, uh, write to the manufacturer?

14:04.995 --> 14:06.411
Or do you just

14:06.413 --> 14:09.580
shrug it off, throw the box
away and get on with your life?

14:09.582 --> 14:10.882
Me? I'd go back to the store.

14:10.884 --> 14:13.501
- Because?
- ‭Any reputable store is gonna want

14:13.503 --> 14:15.386
to make good on that purchase.

14:15.388 --> 14:17.889
And so is the manufacturer, by the way.

14:18.257 --> 14:20.758
There's nothing to be gained
by angering a customer.

14:20.760 --> 14:22.925
This juror's acceptable to the defense.

14:22.927 --> 14:25.146
He's good, but Bull's gonna strike him.

14:25.148 --> 14:27.315
Does the plaintiff wish
to question this juror?

14:27.317 --> 14:30.217
This juror is acceptable to
the plaintiff, too, Your Honor.

14:30.530 --> 14:31.653
Thank you.

14:34.157 --> 14:37.492
If you have a choice, do you
prefer store brand products,

14:37.494 --> 14:39.360
or name brand products?

14:39.362 --> 14:40.778
Most of the time, store brand.

14:40.780 --> 14:42.447
Any particular reason why?

14:42.449 --> 14:44.499
Bears don't use toilet paper.

14:44.501 --> 14:46.417
And mermaids don't drink coffee.

14:46.419 --> 14:48.369
I'm not paying for the trademark.

14:48.371 --> 14:50.371
I'm paying for the product.

14:50.373 --> 14:52.001
- That's very clever.
- ‭Mm-hmm.

14:52.003 --> 14:53.541
Move to strike, Your Honor.

14:55.178 --> 14:56.737
ATTORNEY: How do you feel
about drug companies?

14:56.739 --> 14:58.429
I wish their drugs cost less.

14:58.431 --> 15:00.214
But then... I wish everything cost less.

15:00.216 --> 15:02.300
(LAUGHS) Hear, hear.

15:02.302 --> 15:03.768
But notwithstanding price,

15:03.770 --> 15:05.720
how do you feel about drug companies?

15:05.722 --> 15:08.189
I mean, do you use
prescription drugs at all?

15:08.191 --> 15:09.941
I have a couple of prescriptions, yes.

15:09.943 --> 15:12.143
And do they do
what they're supposed to do?

15:12.145 --> 15:13.609
Help you with the things you

15:13.634 --> 15:15.229
- need them to help with?
- Yes.

15:15.231 --> 15:17.231
Would you miss them
if you didn't have them?

15:17.233 --> 15:18.399
Couldn't get them?

15:18.401 --> 15:19.867
Yes, definitely.

15:19.869 --> 15:21.903
So back to my first question,

15:21.905 --> 15:23.871
how do you feel about drug companies?

15:25.075 --> 15:28.209
I guess I'm kind of grateful for them.

15:28.211 --> 15:30.078
(MOUTHING): She's great.

15:30.080 --> 15:32.580
ATTORNEY: This juror is
acceptable to the defense.

15:32.582 --> 15:34.382
And to the plaintiff, Your Honor.

15:35.184 --> 15:37.719
Ladies and gentlemen, we have a jury.

15:38.129 --> 15:39.983
- The rest of you are dismissed.
- (GAVEL BANGS)

15:39.985 --> 15:41.889
Thank you for your time.

15:44.010 --> 15:45.259
Well, that was easy.

15:45.261 --> 15:46.594
What are you trying to pull?

15:46.596 --> 15:47.895
What are you talking about?

15:47.897 --> 15:49.063
You mean the jurors?

15:49.065 --> 15:51.182
Great minds think alike.

15:52.152 --> 15:53.851
You look puzzled.

15:54.103 --> 15:55.353
Can't you read me?

15:55.355 --> 15:57.188
I'd just like to understand. That's all.

15:57.190 --> 15:58.573
Oh, I'm sorry.

15:58.575 --> 16:00.735
We're not taking new
students at the moment.

16:01.244 --> 16:03.411
See you in court, Ms. Cander.

16:11.616 --> 16:13.750
(ELEVATOR BELL CHIMES)

16:16.091 --> 16:17.819
(SIGHS)

16:20.162 --> 16:21.647
(COMPUTER BEEPS)

16:31.694 --> 16:32.975
Cable.

16:33.467 --> 16:35.050
- Cable!
- ‭(GASPS)

16:35.661 --> 16:37.082
BENNY: So what did you discover working

16:37.084 --> 16:38.417
the graveyard shift?

16:38.419 --> 16:39.325
Bunch of stuff.

16:39.327 --> 16:42.204
A complete record of every
delivery Simon ever made

16:42.206 --> 16:43.672
for Rush City Courier.

16:43.674 --> 16:46.788
And Danny e-mailed me that she
might've found another subject

16:46.790 --> 16:49.461
in Simon's trial, and last but not least,

16:49.463 --> 16:54.049
my very big score...
an old friend of Simon's.

16:54.051 --> 16:56.218
And this friend is relevant why?

16:56.666 --> 16:59.221
I don't know. It's really a long shot.

16:59.223 --> 17:02.608
But the funny thing is, I didn't
even find him on the Internet.

17:02.610 --> 17:05.394
I dug up his application
from when he worked here,

17:05.396 --> 17:08.564
and under emergency contact,
he put this guy.

17:08.566 --> 17:10.065
His name is Tom Greaver.

17:10.067 --> 17:11.400
Never mentioned him to me

17:11.402 --> 17:13.569
the whole time we knew each other, but

17:13.570 --> 17:15.487
put someone as your emergency contact,

17:15.489 --> 17:17.256
they've got to know a lot about you.

17:17.258 --> 17:20.125
Hmm. You should come to court.

17:20.127 --> 17:21.910
We're there because of you.

17:22.441 --> 17:23.744
MRS. JONES: Simon and I

17:23.747 --> 17:25.664
were incredibly close.

17:26.404 --> 17:29.501
We spoke twice a week...
Mondays and Thursdays.

17:29.503 --> 17:31.086
He always called me.

17:31.088 --> 17:33.422
7:30 at night.

17:33.424 --> 17:35.924
You could set your clock by it.

17:35.926 --> 17:38.393
And then one Thursday, um,

17:38.395 --> 17:41.146
a little over two months ago,
my phone didn't ring,

17:41.961 --> 17:43.462
so I worried.

17:44.101 --> 17:46.768
And finally,

17:46.770 --> 17:49.218
despite my better judgment, I called him.

17:50.241 --> 17:51.470
Did he answer?

17:52.471 --> 17:54.159
Yes and no.

17:54.161 --> 17:55.744
How do you mean?

17:55.746 --> 17:59.281
It was Simon, but it wasn't my Simon.

18:00.451 --> 18:02.398
He just sounded different.

18:02.907 --> 18:04.137
Muted.

18:04.955 --> 18:07.122
Like some part of him had disappeared

18:07.124 --> 18:09.791
or... been put away.

18:09.793 --> 18:11.460
And did you know at this point

18:11.462 --> 18:14.546
that he had started the Dep
drug trial three days earlier?

18:14.548 --> 18:15.931
No.

18:16.495 --> 18:18.623
I just knew something was different.

18:19.436 --> 18:21.470
And not for the better.

18:22.460 --> 18:23.689
Your witness.

18:26.371 --> 18:27.893
Earth to TAC.

18:27.895 --> 18:29.015
Tell me what you see.

18:29.017 --> 18:30.896
MARISSA: Well, because of the strategy

18:30.898 --> 18:32.564
you're using of starting with jurors

18:32.566 --> 18:35.233
who are predisposed
to trust big companies,

18:35.235 --> 18:37.653
you're at a disadvantage
coming out of the box.

18:37.655 --> 18:39.488
You began the morning with ten red jurors

18:39.490 --> 18:40.956
and only two green ones.

18:40.958 --> 18:42.207
And that hasn't changed.

18:42.209 --> 18:43.875
But she doesn't know that.

18:43.877 --> 18:45.661
You mean Arti? How could she?

18:45.663 --> 18:47.879
ATTORNEY: Our condolences, Mrs. Jones.

18:47.881 --> 18:50.966
You said your son seemed, uh,

18:50.968 --> 18:52.134
different that day.

18:52.136 --> 18:54.052
- He did.
- ‭Did he mention

18:54.054 --> 18:56.577
to you that he had quit his job?

18:57.007 --> 18:58.256
No, he did not.

18:58.258 --> 19:00.342
Did he mention to you
that he decided instead

19:00.344 --> 19:02.644
to become a bike messenger?

19:03.259 --> 19:04.397
No, he did not.

19:04.399 --> 19:07.683
And you've already testified
that he hadn't confided in you

19:07.685 --> 19:10.319
that he was participating
in a drug trial.

19:10.321 --> 19:13.855
So isn't it a bit... disingenuous

19:13.857 --> 19:16.108
to talk about how close you were?

19:17.098 --> 19:19.077
And couldn't it be that the reason

19:19.079 --> 19:23.198
he sounded... what word
did you use?... muted was because

19:23.200 --> 19:25.033
he was keeping so many secrets from you?

19:25.035 --> 19:26.251
BENNY: Objection!

19:26.253 --> 19:28.670
The counselor has asked
two questions in a row

19:28.672 --> 19:30.422
without letting the witness answer.

19:30.424 --> 19:32.007
Sustained.

19:32.009 --> 19:35.961
Mr. Hansen, if you could
please ask one question

19:35.963 --> 19:38.046
and wait for the witness to answer.

19:39.800 --> 19:43.352
Mrs. Jones, do you have any education

19:43.354 --> 19:46.555
or certification or training of any kind

19:46.557 --> 19:48.807
that allows you to hypothesize

19:48.809 --> 19:51.226
from hearing someone's voice on the phone

19:51.228 --> 19:53.278
whether they have been affected
in any way

19:53.280 --> 19:55.397
by a medication they might have taken?

19:56.053 --> 19:57.866
No, I do not.

20:00.558 --> 20:02.237
No further questions.

20:02.239 --> 20:04.406
There is so little movement
here, I'm starting to wonder

20:04.408 --> 20:06.491
if we're having a systems failure.

20:06.493 --> 20:10.462
I'm trying to put a good face
on this, but you're not helping.

20:14.251 --> 20:16.418
(CROWD CHATTER)

20:18.555 --> 20:20.555
Kevin? Kevin Wright?

20:20.557 --> 20:24.309
Hi. Um, can I ask you some questions

20:24.311 --> 20:26.812
about a clinical trial
you participated in?

20:34.188 --> 20:35.987
You were in the Dep Pharmaceutical

20:35.989 --> 20:37.939
antidepressant trial, yeah?

20:37.941 --> 20:39.574
That was supposed to be confidential.

20:39.576 --> 20:41.109
It's not something I'm really anxious

20:41.111 --> 20:42.600
for people to know about.

20:43.726 --> 20:45.247
I'm sorry if I startled you.

20:45.249 --> 20:46.479
It's just...

20:47.501 --> 20:51.119
one of the other participants,
Simon Jones, died.

20:51.567 --> 20:53.538
Committed suicide, actually.

20:54.875 --> 20:56.572
I'm just trying
to figure out what happened.

20:58.962 --> 21:00.701
Did you know each other well?

21:01.034 --> 21:03.965
Uh, we never really hung
out or anything, but...

21:04.872 --> 21:06.685
we ended up in a lot of the same trials.

21:07.166 --> 21:09.304
Once you do one, and
you see how easy it is,

21:09.306 --> 21:10.878
how much money they pay...

21:12.776 --> 21:15.694
We were both what they
call healthy volunteers,

21:15.696 --> 21:17.927
and there was a big
demand for that, so...

21:19.720 --> 21:21.733
I'm sorry. Uh, my head is spinning.

21:21.735 --> 21:23.368
It's a shock.

21:23.370 --> 21:25.821
Well, forgive me.
What's a healthy volunteer?

21:25.823 --> 21:27.572
Uh, people who don't have the illness

21:27.574 --> 21:29.040
the drug is being tested for.

21:29.042 --> 21:30.208
Got it.

21:30.210 --> 21:31.493
Well, last question.

21:32.191 --> 21:33.703
Why did you drop out of the study?

21:33.705 --> 21:35.630
KEVIN: When I'm not working at the gym,

21:35.632 --> 21:36.965
I'm training for marathons.

21:36.967 --> 21:38.895
I try to do six to eight miles a day.

21:38.897 --> 21:40.469
Been doing it for years.

21:40.471 --> 21:44.256
But a couple of days after
I started the Dep trial, I...

21:44.258 --> 21:45.871
I don't know. I...

21:47.344 --> 21:51.680
I started having these feelings
of... dread.

21:52.128 --> 21:54.850
I was supposed to fly to Chicago
for a friend's wedding.

21:55.256 --> 21:56.799
Couldn't get on the plane.

21:57.321 --> 21:59.354
Became convinced that it was gonna crash.

21:59.969 --> 22:03.859
And that same weekend... I think
it was Saturday morning...

22:03.861 --> 22:05.374
I couldn't get out of bed.

22:05.376 --> 22:08.269
Just skipped training
altogether, and I never do that.

22:08.978 --> 22:11.750
But then the next day, Sunday,

22:11.752 --> 22:13.752
I'm running across Brooklyn Bridge,

22:13.754 --> 22:16.193
and I'm staring down at the water,

22:16.761 --> 22:20.030
and the next thing I know, I stop

22:20.711 --> 22:23.712
and I'm figuring out
how to get over the rail

22:23.714 --> 22:27.288
and onto the crossbeam so I can jump,

22:28.205 --> 22:30.435
because that's what my body wants to do.

22:31.834 --> 22:33.021
It wants to fall.

22:33.919 --> 22:36.024
It wants to be in the water.

22:36.026 --> 22:38.026
It wants to never come back up.

22:40.030 --> 22:43.031
But I stopped myself. I...

22:43.033 --> 22:45.317
sat down there right on the bridge,

22:45.319 --> 22:46.807
tried to breathe.

22:47.204 --> 22:48.684
Called my parents.

22:50.157 --> 22:51.645
I didn't want to die,

22:52.563 --> 22:54.470
but my mind was telling me to let go.

22:55.725 --> 22:57.867
There's nothing scarier
than realizing your brain

22:57.869 --> 22:59.236
is plotting against you.

23:01.852 --> 23:03.477
No further questions, Your Honor.

23:05.993 --> 23:07.505
MARISSA: Ah, things are looking up.

23:07.507 --> 23:10.592
Two of theirs just became two of ours.

23:10.594 --> 23:12.344
(SPEAKING LOW, INDISTINCTLY)

23:12.346 --> 23:15.180
JUDGE: Does the defense have any
questions for the witness?

23:16.099 --> 23:17.963
HANSEN: Morning, sir.

23:18.652 --> 23:20.936
Do you recognize this document?

23:21.550 --> 23:22.821
I-I do.

23:22.823 --> 23:24.272
It's a consent form I signed

23:24.274 --> 23:26.942
to participate in the
Dep Pharmaceutical trial.

23:26.944 --> 23:28.910
And, uh, is this your signature

23:28.912 --> 23:30.412
at the bottom of it?

23:30.414 --> 23:31.382
It is.

23:31.384 --> 23:33.448
And, uh, can you tell us the purpose

23:33.450 --> 23:36.251
of the mandatory washout period?

23:36.253 --> 23:38.776
It's mentioned in the
third paragraph there.

23:39.790 --> 23:44.426
It's, uh, the period of time
between drug trials.

23:44.428 --> 23:46.928
It's something the companies insist on.

23:46.930 --> 23:50.098
It exists to make sure
their drugs don't interact

23:50.100 --> 23:52.434
with someone else's drugs
from an earlier trial.

23:52.436 --> 23:54.803
I think we've just been "Candered."

23:54.805 --> 23:57.305
HANSEN: And on this form you signed,

23:57.307 --> 23:59.975
how long is the specified washout period?

23:59.977 --> 24:02.310
It specifies 30 days.

24:02.312 --> 24:03.561
30 days.

24:03.563 --> 24:06.314
And what were you doing 27 days

24:06.316 --> 24:09.091
before you started the
Dep Pharmaceutical trial?

24:09.093 --> 24:12.287
Remember, you are under oath.

24:13.156 --> 24:14.956
Well, I was doing a lot of things.

24:15.905 --> 24:20.128
But, uh, one of them was,
I was finishing up

24:20.130 --> 24:22.714
the Manhattan Hill Medical
painkiller trial.

24:22.716 --> 24:24.059
Last day, last dose.

24:24.061 --> 24:26.334
And do you happen to know if Simon Jones

24:26.336 --> 24:27.825
was in that trial as well?

24:28.711 --> 24:31.089
Um, yes, he was.

24:31.091 --> 24:33.258
What drug trial are they talking about?

24:33.260 --> 24:34.759
Where are they getting this

24:34.761 --> 24:35.971
and why don't we have it?

24:35.973 --> 24:38.680
HANSEN: Is 27 days
the same thing as 30 days?

24:38.682 --> 24:40.148
- KEVIN: Of course not.
- HANSEN: Then how do you know

24:40.150 --> 24:41.599
it wasn't the interaction
of the painkiller

24:41.601 --> 24:43.234
with the antidepressant that caused

24:43.236 --> 24:45.270
the suicidal ideation
the two of you experienced?

24:45.272 --> 24:48.012
Because... I know.

24:49.096 --> 24:51.498
Look, we've done so many of these things.

24:51.500 --> 24:54.529
And it's... everyone does it.

24:55.102 --> 24:57.332
No further questions.

25:13.029 --> 25:14.963
I don't understand.
You interviewed Kevin.

25:14.988 --> 25:15.980
DANNY: Yeah.

25:16.140 --> 25:18.273
Obviously he didn't tell me
that he and Simon

25:18.275 --> 25:19.377
weren't living up to their consent

25:19.402 --> 25:20.475
- form agreements.
- BULL: Well.

25:20.477 --> 25:22.931
And there was no way of knowing
about the other drug trial.

25:22.933 --> 25:25.697
Drug trials in the research
stages of pre-FDA approval

25:25.699 --> 25:27.332
don't need to be reported.

25:27.334 --> 25:29.625
- Well, Dep knew about it.
- BENNY: No.

25:29.627 --> 25:33.288
My guess is, Manhattan Hill
Medical tipped them off.

25:33.290 --> 25:36.018
These drug companies
are fiercely competitive,

25:36.627 --> 25:39.745
but they don't like the idea
of being taken to the cleaners

25:39.747 --> 25:42.831
by some guinea pig that
they use to pay chump change

25:42.833 --> 25:44.166
to test their new products.

25:44.168 --> 25:45.417
Where are we with the jurors?

25:45.419 --> 25:47.252
Ten against us, two for us.

25:47.254 --> 25:49.254
There's no movement at all?

25:49.256 --> 25:51.473
Sometimes it goes to 11 against us.

25:51.658 --> 25:54.978
How about that
emergency contact guy? Tom?

25:54.980 --> 25:57.846
Tom Greaver. I can't find him.

25:57.848 --> 25:59.428
Nor can I.

25:59.442 --> 26:01.192
He's virtually invisible online.

26:01.668 --> 26:03.945
What about tracking down other
participants in Simon's trial?

26:03.947 --> 26:05.863
(SCOFFS) We're all trying.

26:06.757 --> 26:09.784
Okay. Who is, uh, our
next witness, counselor?

26:10.177 --> 26:13.680
We, uh, really don't have one.

26:16.100 --> 26:17.625
Terrific.

26:18.143 --> 26:19.677
Tomorrow morning when we rest
our non-case,

26:19.679 --> 26:22.039
the only mystery will be,

26:22.041 --> 26:24.598
is the defense gonna have
a field day toying with us,

26:24.600 --> 26:27.726
or will they be humane and ask
for an immediate dismissal?

26:28.513 --> 26:30.072
I'm sorry, Dr. Bull.

26:30.860 --> 26:33.111
I never should have come
to you with this.

26:33.399 --> 26:36.650
Well, that's why I normally
make it a point

26:36.652 --> 26:39.036
not to work on behalf
of immature slackers

26:39.038 --> 26:40.621
who quit without notice,

26:40.623 --> 26:42.372
lie without giving it a second thought,

26:42.374 --> 26:44.541
and jump off rooftops without any regard

26:44.543 --> 26:46.380
for the people they leave behind.

26:47.463 --> 26:49.007
But that's just me.

26:52.167 --> 26:53.220
(SNIFFLES)

26:54.169 --> 26:55.431
(DOOR CLOSES)

26:56.962 --> 26:59.506
- (KNOCKING ON GLASS)
- He's busy.

26:59.508 --> 27:01.758
(DOOR OPENS, FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

27:04.179 --> 27:05.846
Pretty, uh...

27:06.316 --> 27:08.515
Pretty savage out there, huh?

27:08.517 --> 27:10.404
I don't like to lose.

27:11.020 --> 27:12.819
The case or the girl?

27:12.821 --> 27:14.521
Oh, please.

27:14.523 --> 27:18.742
No. You didn't do us
any favors with the jury.

27:18.744 --> 27:22.124
Only people who trust
corporations? That...

27:23.208 --> 27:25.198
That is a hell of a mountain to climb

27:25.200 --> 27:27.629
when you're trying to prove
corporate malfeasance.

27:29.204 --> 27:32.372
And don't try to tell me
it wasn't for that girl.

27:32.885 --> 27:35.258
"I'm Dr. Bull. Here...

27:35.260 --> 27:37.377
"I'll give you the jurors that you want,

27:37.379 --> 27:38.974
and I'll still beat you, right?"

27:39.715 --> 27:40.809
You happy now?

27:41.250 --> 27:42.917
You rode to the rescue and reminded me

27:42.942 --> 27:44.830
there's plenty of blame to go around.

27:44.966 --> 27:46.565
Benny the hero.

27:48.107 --> 27:50.023
Now leave me alone.

27:50.025 --> 27:51.361
I'm preparing for tomorrow.

27:55.898 --> 27:57.493
(DOOR OPENS)

27:59.036 --> 28:00.150
(GAVEL BANGS)

28:00.152 --> 28:01.702
JUDGE: Mr. Hansen, call
your first witness.

28:01.704 --> 28:03.036
HANSEN: The defense would like

28:03.038 --> 28:05.455
to call Tom Greaver to the stand.

28:08.962 --> 28:11.263
- How the hell did they find him?
- (DOOR CLOSES)

28:11.265 --> 28:15.183
The more important question is... why?

28:17.930 --> 28:19.604
TOM: We met in college.

28:19.765 --> 28:21.439
Liked all the same stuff...

28:21.441 --> 28:23.892
drinking beers, listening to music.

28:23.894 --> 28:25.644
Drinking beers?

28:25.646 --> 28:26.945
You know, on Simon's consent form,

28:26.947 --> 28:28.730
he said that he doesn't drink.

28:28.732 --> 28:30.315
Well, this was a long time ago.

28:30.317 --> 28:31.866
We were 18.

28:32.319 --> 28:34.286
I'm pretty sure he was telling the truth.

28:34.947 --> 28:36.237
In fact, I'm certain of it.

28:36.239 --> 28:38.323
And what makes you so certain?

28:38.992 --> 28:40.158
Did something happen?

28:40.160 --> 28:41.411
Yeah.

28:43.330 --> 28:46.041
Around the same time, freshman year,

28:48.168 --> 28:49.801
Simon OD'd on heroin.

28:49.803 --> 28:51.503
- (GASPS)
- (SHOCKED MURMURING)

28:51.505 --> 28:52.721
Oh, my God.

28:52.723 --> 28:54.172
No.

28:54.174 --> 28:55.759
Happened at my house.

28:56.760 --> 28:58.927
He came home with me one weekend.

29:00.264 --> 29:01.980
My mom was an emergency room nurse

29:01.982 --> 29:03.898
and she saved him by giving him Narcan.

29:05.819 --> 29:06.985
No one ever knew.

29:06.987 --> 29:08.353
There was no record.

29:10.816 --> 29:12.691
I know his parents never knew.

29:14.027 --> 29:15.577
After that...

29:17.030 --> 29:18.997
...he just went completely sober.

29:19.658 --> 29:21.952
No drugs, no alcohol, no nothing.

29:22.619 --> 29:24.703
You think the overdose was intentional?

29:24.705 --> 29:27.005
Objection. Counselor calling
for speculation.

29:27.516 --> 29:29.174
I'll withdraw the question.

29:29.585 --> 29:31.876
Yeah, but he can't withdraw
the inference.

29:32.296 --> 29:34.262
She's good, damn it.

29:34.673 --> 29:36.514
She's killing us.

29:37.134 --> 29:39.384
She is representing her client
like a pit bull,

29:39.386 --> 29:41.102
and she's not gonna let a pesky thing

29:41.104 --> 29:42.804
like the truth stand in her way.

29:42.806 --> 29:44.022
MARISSA: Bull, I'm sorry to interrupt,

29:44.024 --> 29:47.058
but we just went to 12 red jurors.

29:47.060 --> 29:49.167
- (COMPUTER BEEPS)
- Yes! Yes, I got it.

29:49.169 --> 29:50.505
I got it.

29:50.507 --> 29:52.781
Tell them to request a recess, a break.

29:53.483 --> 29:54.899
I found him.

29:54.901 --> 29:56.735
I found Tom Greaver.

29:57.571 --> 29:59.270
He changed his name.

30:06.745 --> 30:08.112
So we misdirect here, then we...

30:08.114 --> 30:09.613
BENNY: Cable.

30:10.709 --> 30:12.166
Thank you for these.

30:17.591 --> 30:18.839
I'm really glad you came.

30:18.841 --> 30:20.374
Yeah.

30:20.719 --> 30:21.959
Hope it makes a difference.

30:21.961 --> 30:23.764
Oh, I think it might.

30:25.891 --> 30:27.684
I'm glad you came, too.

30:28.134 --> 30:31.018
And if I was harsh last night...

30:31.020 --> 30:32.272
Oh, you were.

30:33.857 --> 30:35.806
But we've been together a while,

30:35.808 --> 30:37.808
so I know it's only because you care.

30:37.810 --> 30:39.526
I hate to lose.

30:41.948 --> 30:43.147
Let's go with yours.

30:44.618 --> 30:45.649
BENNY: That was, uh...

30:46.119 --> 30:47.818
quite a fascinating story you told

30:47.820 --> 30:49.903
about your friend Simon
just before we adjourned.

30:49.905 --> 30:52.222
It wasn't a story.

30:52.224 --> 30:55.075
I didn't mean to imply anything,
Mr. Greaver.

30:56.296 --> 30:58.078
But I am curious.

30:59.007 --> 31:01.510
Your mom kept Narcan at home?

31:02.001 --> 31:04.657
Well, like I said, she was
an emergency room nurse.

31:04.659 --> 31:05.719
Still...

31:06.223 --> 31:09.640
was she anticipating your best
friend suffering an overdose

31:09.642 --> 31:12.176
or was she just the best
prepared mom on the block?

31:12.178 --> 31:13.977
Objection. Calls for speculation,

31:13.979 --> 31:16.013
and counselor's tone is provocative.

31:16.015 --> 31:17.181
I'll withdraw the question.

31:17.853 --> 31:19.733
Now, if I wanted

31:19.735 --> 31:22.769
to corroborate this story,
who can I speak to?

31:22.771 --> 31:24.855
Say, your mom, or...?

31:24.857 --> 31:26.240
Unfortunately, she passed four years ago.

31:27.202 --> 31:28.825
I'm so sorry to hear that.

31:29.496 --> 31:32.613
Okay. All right. So-so-so let's review.

31:32.615 --> 31:34.248
Your mother's no longer with us.

31:34.250 --> 31:36.033
Simon is no longer with us.

31:36.035 --> 31:38.202
Really, the only person
that we can rely on

31:38.204 --> 31:41.242
regarding the truthfulness
of the story is-is you.

31:41.244 --> 31:42.775
Isn't that correct?

31:42.777 --> 31:44.758
Yeah. I suppose that's true.

31:45.887 --> 31:47.711
The only reason I mention it, is...

31:49.015 --> 31:52.099
we can't find any history
whatsoever on Simon,

31:52.101 --> 31:54.518
with regard to drug use.

31:54.938 --> 31:56.022
None.

31:57.412 --> 32:00.769
But there is quite a dossier
on a fellow named Tom Belmond,

32:01.658 --> 32:03.277
who went to college with you and Simon.

32:04.364 --> 32:06.780
Arrests for, uh, possession.

32:06.782 --> 32:08.439
Arrests for sales of narcotics.

32:08.441 --> 32:09.899
Three hospitalizations

32:09.901 --> 32:11.702
for overdoses, and then,

32:11.704 --> 32:13.070
ultimately, of course, expulsion.

32:13.072 --> 32:14.488
BULL: What's that sound?

32:14.490 --> 32:17.273
Is that the sound of jurors
starting to move?

32:17.275 --> 32:19.793
Do you happen to know a Tom Belmond?

32:21.423 --> 32:22.481
I'm-I'm sorry.

32:22.483 --> 32:24.047
I-I didn't hear your response.

32:24.220 --> 32:25.920
You ever hear of a Tom Belmond?

32:28.174 --> 32:30.091
I see, you're-you're having
trouble with this.

32:30.093 --> 32:33.511
Okay. All right. I-I'll make it
a little easier for you.

32:34.853 --> 32:36.230
Aren't you Tom Belmond?

32:36.232 --> 32:38.599
Objection. Is the attorney
asking questions

32:38.601 --> 32:40.818
or making third party pronouncements?

32:40.820 --> 32:42.019
Sustained.

32:42.021 --> 32:43.404
Ask a question, counselor.

32:43.406 --> 32:44.772
I'm sorry, Your Honor.

32:44.774 --> 32:47.108
You just got back your two
jurors from yesterday.

32:47.110 --> 32:49.410
- I feel the wind shifting.
- BENNY: Didn't you change your name

32:49.412 --> 32:51.779
from Tom Belmond
to Tom Greaver precisely,

32:51.781 --> 32:53.448
so you can avoid having to mention

32:53.450 --> 32:55.366
your arrest history,
your history with drugs,

32:55.368 --> 32:57.668
while seeking employment and housing...

32:57.670 --> 33:00.421
I wanted a fresh start, okay?

33:00.423 --> 33:02.457
I made a lot of mistakes as a kid, but...

33:02.459 --> 33:05.009
MARISSA: One more just came over.

33:05.011 --> 33:07.545
- We are now at nine red and three green.
- BENNY: And isn't it true

33:07.547 --> 33:09.680
your mother smuggled Narcan
out of the emergency room,

33:09.682 --> 33:12.016
not because she was worried about Simon,

33:12.018 --> 33:13.801
who had no interest in drugs,

33:13.803 --> 33:15.603
but because she was terrified

33:15.605 --> 33:17.472
that her own son might overdose one day?

33:17.474 --> 33:18.856
- Objection.
- And the story

33:18.858 --> 33:21.893
about Simon Jones
attempting to commit suicide

33:21.895 --> 33:23.811
eight years ago with heroin
was just that.

33:23.813 --> 33:25.646
- It was just a story, right?
- Objection.

33:25.648 --> 33:28.649
Again, these are pronouncements,
not questions, Your Honor.

33:28.651 --> 33:30.985
One more green light.

33:30.987 --> 33:33.204
They've got eight, and we've got four.

33:33.206 --> 33:34.822
Now the fun really begins.

33:34.824 --> 33:37.041
Well, then, here's the question:
how much did Dep pay you

33:37.043 --> 33:39.494
to take the stand
and perjure yourself today,

33:39.496 --> 33:41.295
Mr. Greaver or Mr. Belmond,

33:41.297 --> 33:43.047
- or whoever you say you are?!
- Objection,

33:43.049 --> 33:44.499
- Your Honor.
- Sustained.

33:44.501 --> 33:45.833
No problem, Your Honor.

33:46.132 --> 33:48.302
- Question withdrawn.
- (GALLEY MURMURING)

33:48.860 --> 33:49.887
I think I'd rather not know.

33:49.889 --> 33:52.173
No further questions, please.

33:53.098 --> 33:54.509
How's that for an inference?

33:54.511 --> 33:55.893
MARISSA: Now we've got five,

33:55.895 --> 33:57.011
and they've got seven.

33:57.013 --> 33:58.396
BULL: Nice work.

33:58.398 --> 34:00.681
JUDGE: Court will resume
tomorrow morning.

34:02.519 --> 34:04.519
Read any good jurors lately?

34:04.521 --> 34:06.153
Well, yes, I have.

34:06.528 --> 34:08.856
And I suspect that you have, too.

34:09.239 --> 34:10.690
But we both know that I'm reading

34:10.693 --> 34:12.360
more good jurors than you are, Dr. Bull,

34:12.362 --> 34:14.529
so stop trying to play with me.

34:15.245 --> 34:16.531
Although, I suspect

34:16.533 --> 34:19.951
that at some point,
we might get to that, too.

34:20.786 --> 34:22.954
(TRAFFIC SOUNDS)

34:26.376 --> 34:28.543
(POUNDING ON DOOR)

34:31.431 --> 34:33.547
Hi. Sorry to bother you.

34:33.550 --> 34:35.766
I'm looking for Edgar Paulson?

34:41.605 --> 34:43.190
CHUNK: Mr. Paulson's name

34:43.192 --> 34:44.725
is on a list of people who participated

34:44.726 --> 34:47.027
in a drug trial that we're investigating.

34:47.030 --> 34:48.696
(CHUCKLES): It took me a
while to track him down.

34:48.697 --> 34:50.982
Is there any way I could speak to him?

34:50.984 --> 34:54.068
I'm sorry. Uh, Mr. Paulson's
no longer with us.

34:54.701 --> 34:57.822
Is there any way you could share
a forwarding address?

34:57.824 --> 34:59.740
Some way to contact him?

35:01.458 --> 35:03.828
Mr. Paulson hung himself

35:04.336 --> 35:05.997
about three and a half weeks ago.

35:05.999 --> 35:07.715
(EXHALES)

35:08.214 --> 35:10.134
I'm so sorry.

35:10.508 --> 35:11.552
I had no idea.

35:11.554 --> 35:13.754
I actually checked
all the names on this list

35:13.756 --> 35:15.806
for deaths and hospitalizations.

35:15.808 --> 35:18.009
I don't know how that got past me.

35:18.266 --> 35:19.844
I'm sure it'll show up shortly.

35:19.846 --> 35:21.820
The woman who took care of him,

35:22.312 --> 35:23.981
she struck me as very thorough.

35:23.983 --> 35:25.316
A woman?

35:25.318 --> 35:28.152
Well, someone he worked with. Or for.

35:28.526 --> 35:30.104
She would stop by here.

35:30.445 --> 35:31.989
Make sure he took his medicine.

35:32.364 --> 35:34.075
Gave him money occasionally.

35:34.866 --> 35:36.944
She stopped by to see him
the morning we found him.

35:36.946 --> 35:39.163
She was terribly upset.

35:39.579 --> 35:41.282
Took care of all the details.

35:41.414 --> 35:43.618
Even paid for his cremation.

35:44.751 --> 35:47.625
Would you happen to have
her name? This woman?

35:47.627 --> 35:49.365
TESSA: My name is Tessa Snyder.

35:49.367 --> 35:52.593
I am Chief Executive Officer
for Dep Pharmaceutical.

35:52.595 --> 35:54.462
Have been for about three years now.

35:54.464 --> 35:56.097
And can you tell the jury

35:56.099 --> 35:57.798
what we're doing here today?

35:57.800 --> 36:00.601
And by that I mean
we all know drug companies

36:00.603 --> 36:03.437
face legal actions like this
all the time.

36:03.439 --> 36:05.473
Usually they're settled out of court.

36:05.475 --> 36:08.976
But why did you, a young CEO,
choose to fight this out

36:08.978 --> 36:11.016
- in a public forum?
- ‭BULL: Nice move.

36:11.018 --> 36:13.614
She's turning the very fact
that we're suing her client

36:13.616 --> 36:16.233
into a laudable thing
in the eyes of the jury.

36:16.616 --> 36:18.319
I may steal that.

36:19.739 --> 36:23.144
One, this company
has an unblemished record

36:23.146 --> 36:25.409
with regard to drug and testing safety.

36:25.750 --> 36:29.080
And two, this new drug...

36:29.082 --> 36:31.966
the first created under my leadership...

36:32.507 --> 36:34.835
is truly a pharmaceutical miracle

36:34.837 --> 36:37.254
for people who suffer from depression.

36:37.721 --> 36:41.225
I welcomed the opportunity
to tell the court,

36:41.227 --> 36:43.626
the jury, the world, about it.

36:43.628 --> 36:45.370
And can you tell the jury

36:45.886 --> 36:46.931
why you conduct

36:46.933 --> 36:48.773
these clinical trials?

36:48.798 --> 36:50.768
Well, the first thing you need to know

36:50.770 --> 36:54.739
is I got into this business to help ease

36:54.741 --> 36:56.323
human suffering.

36:56.781 --> 36:58.075
I mention that

36:58.077 --> 37:01.529
because I need you to know
how deeply sorry I am

37:01.531 --> 37:02.863
for the Jones family's loss.

37:02.865 --> 37:06.054
BULL: Excellent segue. Nicely written.

37:06.056 --> 37:07.368
Nicely performed.

37:07.370 --> 37:08.836
Having said that,

37:08.838 --> 37:11.038
we did nothing wrong.

37:11.421 --> 37:13.841
Simon was screened.

37:13.843 --> 37:16.544
The fact that he was not
completely truthful

37:16.546 --> 37:18.012
is not something we can control.

37:18.014 --> 37:19.263
MARISSA: Just so you know,

37:19.265 --> 37:21.432
our mirror jury is loving her.

37:21.434 --> 37:22.717
How can you not?

37:27.020 --> 37:29.557
And while we need to do better

37:29.559 --> 37:30.891
to ferret out the liars,

37:30.893 --> 37:32.893
we can't let it stop our work.

37:32.895 --> 37:35.824
These clinical trials
exist for the greater good.

37:35.826 --> 37:37.198
Without them,

37:37.200 --> 37:40.339
there wouldn't be medical
innovations and discoveries,

37:40.341 --> 37:42.119
new cures for everything

37:42.121 --> 37:44.488
from reproductive health to cancer.

37:44.490 --> 37:46.123
BULL: Something's going on.

37:46.125 --> 37:48.826
She's targeting juror three. Why?

37:48.828 --> 37:51.559
Well, she's one of our greens,
and she just went red.

37:51.561 --> 37:54.048
Her friend recently passed from cancer.

37:54.050 --> 37:57.551
Wow. This woman will do anything to win.

37:57.553 --> 37:59.420
Reminds me of me.

38:03.389 --> 38:04.892
BENNY: Good morning, Ms. Snyder.

38:04.894 --> 38:06.977
Isn't it true
that one of the major problems

38:06.979 --> 38:10.848
these clinical trials face
is recruiting subjects?

38:10.850 --> 38:14.602
I mean... I can't believe
that there's lots of people

38:14.604 --> 38:17.938
who are willing to put
untested drugs into their bodies

38:17.940 --> 38:19.940
for whatever you're willing to pay them.

38:19.942 --> 38:22.943
Well, it's certainly a lot easier

38:22.945 --> 38:25.079
to find subjects who suffer
from whatever condition

38:25.081 --> 38:26.460
we're trying to target.

38:27.416 --> 38:28.449
Yes.

38:28.915 --> 38:30.451
It can be incredibly difficult

38:30.453 --> 38:32.870
finding healthy volunteers.

38:32.872 --> 38:34.955
Truly healthy volunteers.

38:35.421 --> 38:38.959
BENNY: And yet, until this
drug, until this lawsuit,

38:38.961 --> 38:41.128
your company had a rare spotless record.

38:41.678 --> 38:43.806
None of the healthy volunteers

38:43.808 --> 38:45.349
in the 50 so years

38:45.351 --> 38:47.134
that the company
has been in existence ever...

38:47.517 --> 38:49.854
filed a claim or sought a settlement.

38:50.626 --> 38:52.857
Is that why you decided
to hide the other suicide

38:52.859 --> 38:54.441
amongst the ten healthy volunteers?

38:54.443 --> 38:56.026
(SHOCKED MURMURING)

39:00.099 --> 39:01.365
I love that sound.

39:01.367 --> 39:03.450
Me, too.

39:03.452 --> 39:05.319
I have no idea what you're talking about.

39:05.321 --> 39:08.205
Well, does the name
Edgar Paulson ring a bell?

39:10.790 --> 39:13.160
Edgar Paulson?

39:13.162 --> 39:15.079
A 62-year-old homeless man

39:15.081 --> 39:17.331
with dubious mental acuity

39:17.333 --> 39:20.167
who, up until the point
that he hung himself,

39:20.169 --> 39:23.386
was living at the Light
Mission Homeless Shelter?

39:24.345 --> 39:26.557
Is that Dep Pharmaceutical's idea

39:26.559 --> 39:28.509
of a healthy volunteer?

39:29.578 --> 39:31.744
MARISSA: Things are looking
greener and greener over here.

39:32.562 --> 39:34.272
I think you're mistaken.

39:35.523 --> 39:37.985
Mr. Paulson was in absolutely fine...

39:37.987 --> 39:40.688
physical and mental shape.

39:40.690 --> 39:43.240
He had fallen on hard times financially,

39:43.242 --> 39:45.576
and that had taken a toll
on his disposition.

39:45.578 --> 39:48.445
But from a purely clinical standpoint,

39:48.447 --> 39:50.581
Mr. Paulson was an ideal subject.

39:50.583 --> 39:54.368
Additionally, he finished
the trial successfully.

39:55.001 --> 39:57.371
Anything that may
have befallen him after that...

39:57.373 --> 39:58.873
Six days after that?

39:58.875 --> 40:00.541
Again, Mr. Paulson

40:00.543 --> 40:04.545
suffered from crushing
financial problems.

40:05.053 --> 40:07.715
I can only speculate that that
may be why he took his own life.

40:08.139 --> 40:10.725
- There's no causation there.
- Ah.

40:11.701 --> 40:13.888
I guess we'll never know,
will we, Ms. Snyder?

40:13.890 --> 40:16.523
Since you conveniently paid
for the body to be cremated.

40:16.525 --> 40:17.775
(SHOCKED MURMURING)

40:17.777 --> 40:18.809
Objection.

40:18.811 --> 40:20.091
Relevance.

40:20.093 --> 40:22.029
Doesn't get more relevant than that.

40:22.031 --> 40:25.399
But please ask the witness a question

40:25.401 --> 40:27.985
as opposed to simply making a statement.

40:27.987 --> 40:30.788
Yes. Ms. Snyder,

40:31.079 --> 40:33.657
did you or did you not

40:33.659 --> 40:36.493
arrange for the cremation
of Mr. Edgar Paulson

40:36.918 --> 40:39.046
once you realized he had killed himself

40:39.048 --> 40:42.049
after a one month course
of your new drug?

40:44.053 --> 40:46.420
(WHISPERING)

40:47.637 --> 40:48.889
Ms. Snyder?

40:50.927 --> 40:52.476
BULL: Three...

40:53.935 --> 40:55.429
two...

40:56.983 --> 40:58.399
...one.

41:00.403 --> 41:03.437
Your Honor, would it be possible
to ask for a brief recess

41:03.439 --> 41:05.105
so the sides could meet privately

41:05.107 --> 41:06.573
for a short discussion?

41:06.575 --> 41:08.943
Can you say "settlement"?

41:08.945 --> 41:11.245
JUDGE: This court will take
a 90 minute recess.

41:11.247 --> 41:12.613
(GAVEL BANGS)

41:12.615 --> 41:14.415
(GALLERY MURMURING)

41:30.433 --> 41:32.099
(GENTLE PIANO MUSIC PLAYS IN BACKGROUND)

41:32.101 --> 41:33.717
(DOOR OPENS)

41:34.600 --> 41:36.136
- (DOOR CLOSES)
- BULL: Oh.

41:37.520 --> 41:39.440
There you are.

41:39.442 --> 41:41.725
- Here I am.
- ‭Oh.

41:41.727 --> 41:44.812
- Miss?
- Uh, your oldest Scotch. Neat.

41:44.814 --> 41:46.447
And a glass of water, please.

41:46.449 --> 41:47.982
- Okay.
- ‭(CHUCKLES)

41:47.984 --> 41:49.650
(SIGHS)

41:49.652 --> 41:51.618
You read my mind.

41:51.620 --> 41:53.904
But, then again, that's what you do.

41:54.370 --> 41:56.373
And you do it very well, by the way.

41:59.834 --> 42:01.712
I, uh...

42:03.713 --> 42:05.798
I need you to know something.

42:07.008 --> 42:09.067
I didn't bribe that friend of Simon's.

42:09.527 --> 42:10.504
I'm not saying

42:10.506 --> 42:12.973
that I didn't sense that
something might be afoot, but...

42:12.975 --> 42:15.092
I need you to know something.

42:16.017 --> 42:18.929
In the same way you inferred,
without saying as much,

42:18.931 --> 42:21.181
that Simon attempted suicide
with heroin...

42:21.183 --> 42:24.401
even though I strongly suspect
that's not what happened...

42:26.110 --> 42:27.602
Benny and I

42:27.604 --> 42:31.075
decided to infer a little something

42:31.077 --> 42:33.410
that we had no way of knowing was true.

42:34.077 --> 42:35.362
Maybe someone bribed him.

42:35.364 --> 42:37.288
Maybe someone didn't.

42:38.748 --> 42:40.200
We took a shot.

42:42.088 --> 42:43.586
Thank you.

